intro:
Variables aren't limited to strings and numbers. You can stash a whole **object** in a variable and reuse it.

This is the foundation of every DRY pattern in AbstractMenus configs - shared click actions, repeating styles, common item shapes. Define once, reference many times.

```
closeBtnAction { closeMenu = true }

items = [
  {
    slot = 8
    material = BARRIER
    name = "&cClose"
    click { actions = ${closeBtnAction} }
  }
]
# items[0].click.actions resolves to { closeMenu = true }
```

When `${closeBtnAction}` resolves to an object, the whole object lands at that position. Same mechanic as the scalar variable from the previous lesson, just a bigger payload.

The custom key (`closeBtnAction`) sits at the top of the file as a reusable definition; AbstractMenus ignores it after substitution.

**Goal:** define `closeBtnAction` as an object with `closeMenu = true`, then assign it to the existing item's `click.actions`.

starter:
title = "Shop"
size = 3
items = [
  {
    slot = 8
    material = BARRIER
    name = "&cClose"
  }
]

